In this tutorial, you will learn:
- How to sort 5-card poker hands by rank

string.text: This room shows how to sort poker hands by rank.  Press one of the numbered deal buttons in the blue box, which starts a series of processes separated out into multiple buttons.  The process is broken down into multiple steps to make it easier to understand.  After recalling and dealing x cards to each of 10 holders, the 'Get Hand String' button is next.  It uses a custom key to create a string which will be compared to a list of all possible 9,841 equivalence class poker hands available with 1-5 cards.  The 'Compare Hands' button evaluates that string against an array of all possible hand combinations to get the rank/worth of the cards in each holder.  It then selects the highest and lowest value hands and turns the holder green or red.  The 'Rearrange Holders' button moves the holders so they are displayed, in order, from best poker hand to worst.  The 'Hand Type' button uses an array to update the label at the bottom of the holder to identify the type of hand: straight flush (SF), four of a kind (4K), full house (FH), flush (F), straight (S), three of a kind (3K), two pair (2P), one pair (1P), or high card (HC).  This algorithm always treats aces as high, which could be a problem for evaluating low hands as 6-4-3-2-A is the best low hand in some versions of poker. If any hands are identical in this room, the holders will be stacked on top of each other.
